In Ruby, both dup and clone are used to create a copy of an object — but they are not exactly the same.

Let’s understand from scratch.

1️⃣ Basic Difference
Feature	dup	clone
Copies object	✅ Yes	✅ Yes
Copies singleton methods	❌ No	✅ Yes
Copies frozen state	❌ No	✅ Yes
Copies tainted/trusted state	❌ No	✅ Yes
2️⃣ Main Concept
👉 dup

Makes a shallow copy

Does NOT copy singleton methods

Does NOT preserve frozen state

👉 clone

Makes a shallow copy

Copies everything

Preserves:

Singleton methods

Frozen state

Tainted state

3️⃣ Example 1 — Frozen Object
str = "hello"
str.freeze

a = str.dup
b = str.clone

puts a.frozen?   # false
puts b.frozen?   # true
Why?

dup → removes frozen state

clone → keeps frozen state

4️⃣ Example 2 — Singleton Method
obj = "hello"

def obj.greet
  "hi!"
end

a = obj.dup
b = obj.clone

a.greet   # ❌ NoMethodError
b.greet   # ✅ "hi!"
Why?

dup does NOT copy singleton methods

clone copies them

5️⃣ Important: Both Are Shallow Copies

They do NOT deeply copy nested objects.

arr1 = [[1,2]]
arr2 = arr1.dup

arr2[0] << 3

p arr1  # [[1,2,3]]

Inner array is shared.

6️⃣ When To Use What?
✅ Use dup (Most Common)

When you just want a copy

When you don’t care about frozen state

Normal object duplication

✅ Use clone

When you want exact replica

When frozen state matters

When singleton methods must be preserved

7️⃣ Real-World Rule

👉 95% of the time, use dup
👉 Use clone only when you specifically need to preserve object state exactly.

🎯 Simple Memory Trick

dup = duplicate basic

clone = clone exact